                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p rend=\"align(right)\">\n                                        <placeName>Barbados</placeName>\n                                        <date>21 Nov. 1847</date>\n                              </p>\n                              <p>\n                                        <addressee>Revd. Isaac Leeser</addressee>\n                              </p>\n                              <p rend=\"indent(1)\">Dear Sir</p>\n                              <p rend=\"indent(2)\">I have much pleasure in acknowledging<lb/> receipt\n                                        your esteemed favor 3 ultimo, and after the same<lb/> was in\n                                        my possession[?] five days, I received the \"occidents\"<lb/>\n                                        which I have delivered to your several subscribers, and<lb/>\n                                        only two days ago the parcel directed to the Consul<lb/> at\n                                                  <placeName>Grenada</placeName>. I am sorry to say\n                                        I have had a deal<lb/> of trouble ere the latter could be\n                                        obtained, and then had<lb/> to pay $50 freight on it–for\n                                        your guidance and future<lb/> government, I must inform you\n                                        that the Captain of<lb/> the \"Kingston\" Committed a breach\n                                        of trust by opening<lb/> the parcel to ascertain the\n                                        contents, this he cannot deny,<lb/> as he publicly told my\n                                        Father in Law <persName>M. M. I. D.\n                                        Azive</persName>-<lb/>-do, had it have been of the greatest\n                                        consequence he<lb/> would have done the same, therefore I\n                                        consider it a duty<lb/> you owe to yourself to represent his\n                                        conduct to his<lb/> employer, and as you are I understand\n                                        intimate with<lb/> the Several Editors of the Press, that\n                                        you request them<lb/> to give publicity to the same, so that\n                                        the public may<lb/> be guarded against such a man, for he\n                                        would not<lb/> hesitate in my opinion to gratify his\n                                        curiosity to open<lb/> any letter that may be entrusted to\n                                        his care, my Father<lb/> told him, that his conduct should\n                                        be represented,<lb/> when he made for answer \"if that was\n                                        the case<lb/> he would never take charge of any more letter\n                                        or<lb/> parcels from any of our friends\"–this you need\n                                        not<lb/> care</p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3125r22v/canvas/p1"
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
