                  "type": "Annotation",
                  "motivation": "commenting",
                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p>about, for should the \"Kingston\" at any time be put<lb/> up for\n                                        this port, you can always send any thing you<lb/> may have\n                                        under cover <del>of</del>\n                                        <persName>S. P. Musson Esq.</persName> Addressing that<lb/>\n                                        Gentn. A few lines, requesting him to deliver it over to\n                                        me,<lb/> but let it be in a different hand writing to\n                                        yours–<lb/> I must now also acquaint you that some time\n                                        back<lb/> I received a parcel of your \"occidents\" through\n                                        the Post<lb/> Office from one of the Islands, as the Catn.\n                                        Of the vessel<lb/> did not dispose of his cargo here, and\n                                        tried another<lb/> market, and took all letters and parcels\n                                        with him,<lb/> and for which I had to pay $1.25 postage,\n                                        which I<lb/> shall deduct together with the ¢50 now paid,\n                                        when<lb/> I remit you the annual subscription to the\n                                        \"Occident\"<lb/> by the first conveyance, the Books shall be\n                                        forwarded<lb/> to <placeName>Grenada</placeName>, and in\n                                        future should you have any<lb/> thing to send under my care,\n                                        be particular in re-<lb/>-questing the Captn. to deliver\n                                        them on arrival to<lb/> the health officer when he boards\n                                        the vessel, as you<lb/> cannot imagine the trouble I\n                                        invariably have<lb/> with them–my Father has by this\n                                        conveyance<lb/> addressed my sister also on the Subject, and\n                                        in <sic>re-<lb/>-ferance</sic> to her you will learn all\n                                        particulars.–I<lb/> am obliged for your attention in having\n                                        inserted<lb/> the proceedings of our vestry meeting, and in\n                                        all<lb/> consider the October number very interesting–I<lb/>\n                                        am sorry to say up to the present I have not<lb/> received\n                                        the missing or August numbers, nor of it<lb/> the daily\n                                        service you sent by the same vessel,<lb/> and of which I\n                                        some time back communicated</p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3125r22v/canvas/p2"
                }
              ]
